column2: What is your chosen specialty? - Selected Choice

column1: Q58 - What year of medical school did you decide on your chosen specialty?

column2: What year of medical school did you decide on your chosen specialty?

column1: Q46 - Please briefly state the main reason(s) for your decision to pursue this specialty:
Please briefly state the main reason(s) for your decision to pursue this specialty:
love of working with kids, pediatric disease pathology, opportunities for advocacy
Interest in cancer research; fits my personality; slower pace and more time for deeper investigation
Patient relationships and quality of life
Liked IM liked peds. Like all those patients
Covers a broad range of situations in medicine, allows me to continue to be a physician, scientist, activist, I can be a useful doctor in most every-day situations.
It is the patient population that I feel most passionate about even after trying out different fields through third year rotations

It was the only one that called to me when I did it. Acuity of complaints, diversity of problems, underserved patient populations, mix of procedural and diagnostics, culture and atmosphere of practice.
1. Strong Mentorship, 2. Success in electives+ Accolades,  3. Conformed with my vision of type of physician I wished to be
Type of patient relationships, personality fit with other residents, opportunities for fellowship and future careers in academic medicine
I like it more than anything else; strong mentors, exciting field
Advocacy, procedural specialty, patient population, applicability to global health
Personal fulfillment, mental health is important, enjoyed working with patients here the most
Variety in day-to-day practice and focus on women’s health.

Wanted to do primary care. Realized I really enjoyed peds a lot, wanted to be fully boarded in it. Also realized I didn’t care as much for Obstetrics or surgery, so I chose MP over FM. Also wanted the icu training to care for complex patients in the outpatient
Procedural but not surgical hours, Interest in prehospital care
I like cardiopulmonary physiology and critical care. I wanted a good work life balance with a good salary.
Combines being a generalist as well as subspecialist. Also combines surgery and medicine. Felt passionate about advocating for women's health
I want to do hospitalist work for the entire age spectrum
Diversity of patient complaints, procedures, life style
patient population, preventative medicine and surgery, variety in scope of practice
Procedures plus pharm and physiology, good lifestyle, everyone i met was extremely nice and interested in teaching me
Interest in physiology, patient-interaction, research. Did not like surgery culture.
Enjoyed the skill set you focus on and the people/environment that comes with
Day-to-day work flow, people in the specialty, mentorship received
Gestalt of how I felt on the service, how attendings approached decisions, how happy residents were, and how passionate and curious neurologists are
clinic + OR schedule breakdown; interactive clinic exam; patient follow-up; ability to both diagnose and treat patient issues; lifestyle; salary
worked in urology and met good mentors
Personal interests, biomechanical properties, surgical speciality, people in field
Mentors in internal medicine, 3rd year clerkships
love of working with children, pediatric pathologies, culture of teaching, dedication to advocacy
Broad patient population and treatment options (medical, procedural, or social). Fast-paced environment. Master resuscitationist.
mentorship, good elective experience, personality of specialty, subspecialty flexibility, work-life balance
Positive experience during rotations. Did not like EM or surgery. Did like being primary team for patients
continuity of care, ability to care for complex chronic conditions
Meticulous surgeries that are detail-oriented and very "neat". Great mix of clinic and surgery. Regular hours. Physical exam is paramount
The undifferentiated patients, breadth of medicine, and ability to care for a uniquely vulnerable patient population.
Combination of surgical and medicine. Trauma and critical care included.
great mentorship in the field that talked about all of the opportunities

1. Specialty with most direct application of cellular biology to patient care, 2. Diagnostic - as opposed to other diagnostic specialties (i.e. radiology), pathology is more definitive, 3. As a diagnostic specialty, you impact a greater number of patients on any given day, 4. Abundant research opportunities spanning basic science to translational and clinical projects
Patient population, diversity of pathologies and procedures, advancements in research, career satisfaction
Transitions of care, global health opportunities, keeps lots of doors open
It was the most fun, the people were friendly and invested in teaching, the time passes by quickly, I like being active and working with my hands
interest in women’s health and surgery
Gut feeling, found IM rotations really interesting, like fellowship options
Cerebral and procedural field + good pay + good job market + good patient interactions + complex and intellectually stimulating
Mix of OR and clinic time, advocacy for reproductive justice, and caring for women in some of the most vulnerable periods of their lives
Diversity of patients, pathology, and procedures
Wide range of cases, procedural, flexible in terms of lifestyle, can do DR when get old and cranky, pays well, looooots of innovation
I'm a visual learner (localizaing lesions), camaraderie among attending/residents, what I can do for patients/the families
Microsurgeries, mixture of clinic and surgery, very little inpatient time, getting along well with other residents/physicians, interest in vision, lots of active research
I find illnesses that affect children fascinating and I am refreshed by long-term positive outcomes.
I really liked the combined aspects of surgery and medicine, and i had great research Mentorship
I enjoy the ability to think about the patient as a whole while understanding pathophysiology behind disease processes and how they connect.
Flexibility in specialty, respect in the physician community, good mentors, ethnically diverse community, good pay
I was passionate about the patient population and although I enjoyed many of my rotations, I felt that pediatrics was able to combine my interests in each field to be the best fit for me.
Flexibility within subspecialty to pursue multiple career options, can choose to be generalist vs specialist, multidisclipinary field,
Breadth of pathologies encountered, high impact on patient care, emphasis on reading/studying during training, very good compensation/lifestyle.
I was always leaning toward some kind of surgery, but I fell in love with general surgery on my core clerkship
1) turns out I love surgery, 2) the people, 3) breadth of subspecialty options after residency, 4) patients generally healthy before surgery
I chose this specialty before I even started medial school. I love the patients, the balance of surgery and medicine, and the support for progressive causes.
Great lifestyle, great variety in your shifts, great people who you work with, and great mix of required medical knowledge and procedural skills
Intellectual curiosity, personalities observed, consultant nature within a medical team, lifestyle factors
Values of the specialty, scope of care.
Specific rather than general field, interesting disease processes, broad variety of acuity and patient population, good work/life balance
Great mentors in the field, experiences with residents and attendings, skill set desired as physician, work life balance
Variety of patients and body systems
Interest in pathologies, intensive care aspect, and personal experience as a patient
Patient population, Approach to clinical reasoning, support for and track record of research oriented career, job opportunities
Work-life balance, patient population (working with children), large number of subspecialty options to choose from
I went to medical school because I wanted to be a specific type of surgeon
I enjoy the undifferentiated patient and thinking about complex problems from multiple perspectives
Opportunities to participate in medical education, interest in the nervous system
Relationships with patients, intellectually challenging, potential for further fellowship training (cardiology)
General interest in field combined w/opportunity for critical care; leaves open possibility of pursuing fellowship in intervention

Broad depth of knowledge, direct patient care, procedural specialties available for fellowship, longitudinal patient care and acute patient care inpatient, diverse breadth of specialty, diverse patient age
Enjoying surgery with a balance of clinic. Genuine interest in patient population and types of problems encountered
Specialty sounded very interesting to me and I felt like I would enjoy it
Cardiac physiology and pathophysiology are interesting to me
Opportunities for research and patient care.
I felt like i fit in with the residents, lifestyle, broad knowledge
Depth and breadth of knowledge base, fit
Interest in anatomic and pathologic diagnosis; interst in technology; day to day mental dedication to field of interest vs other aspects of medicine.
Had been interested for since undergrad but 3rd year rotation confirmed. I like talking to patients and exploring their stories.
I fell in love with L&D and obstetrics. The workflow seems to fit my desire to stay busy at work.

Came into med school decided on FM because of amazing shadowing experience with an FM doc during undergrad. Hesitate during M2 due to focus on time and efficiency of appts. During M3 saw FM doctors practicing the way I aspired to and felt like I could still do FM despite of all the systemic barriers.
Liked the surgeries and the people. Don't like high morbidity surgery.
Type of work aligned with my personality and goals best
numerous different avenues for specialization, team-based, challenges of diagnosis and management, enjoyed working with other IM residents
Diverse opportunities for practice (primary care, surgery, procedures), longitudinal relationships with patients, patient population
I am doing IM in order to later specialize in Critical Care and Palliative Care
good job market, geographic flexibility for matching, best personalities, lots of intelligent, thoughtful students choose it, high research potential, hated almost everything else
ID after IM: Curative, non-procedural. There is a problem to fix and it is usually fixable.

Always had it as an option in the back of my mind, going through third year rotations helped me realize what I liked and what I didn't like in each rotation and that my chosen specialty was the best fit for me
Previous sports injuries. Opportunities to quickly better quality of life for patients.

Prior work in EMS, enjoy the culture of the field, attendings/residents were interesting people and good educators on clerkship, good pay, less demanding schedule than many other fields, no clinic time, no clinical responsibilities when home, interesting fellowship and career advancement opportunities, influence from near-peer mentors in field, interesting clinical content, personal characteristics meet the needs of the work environment.

Actually decided prior to medical school but that was not an option. I enjoy children as my patient population and pediatrics allows you to go into many different fields of medicine after selecting children as your patient population.
Interest in field. Culture. Shift work.
Variety of patient complaints, schedule, residency training length, career opportunities, attending lifestyle

Personality of ortho residents and attendings I met during rotations, potential income especially considering medical school loan debt, anatomy, types of procedures and specialties within orthopaedics, room for flexibility/creativity in surgeries, ability to work with a wide variety of patients (young versus old, and medically complex versus simple patients), interest in trauma
Enjoyed the immediate gratification of surgery. Hands on specialty. Always felt interesting and the interventions were tangible and effective from my POV. Got along with the residents really well.
Mentorship, complex/interesting cases, not algorithmic, focus on history and exam, subspecialty diversity
Interest in procedures and physiology, work-life balance
Research, longitudinal patient care, many options for after
they are my people. i get to be a generalist while specializing in resuscitation. it is procedural but not surgery. i wanted shiftwork.
Continuity of care with high tech imaging modalities and a cancer focus. Also great lifestyle and compensation

It was my original interest, it was my vision of what "being a doctor" would be like, I enjoyed the collegiality of the field and the residents/attendings I worked with during my 3rd year clerkship, enjoy the academic challenge of working up a patient, enjoy actually sitting down and talking with patients
Good work-life balance + interest in the specialty
I loved surgery, but wanted a mix of surgery and medicine. And the people in urology were amazing. I felt like I fit in
Enjoyed the variety of roles and responsibilities
Variety of pathology seen, good mix between medical and procedural work, good work/life balance
Team work, acuity, social mission, abundance of fellowships
longitudinal relationships, having to know all the specialities- seeing the big picture of a patient's health
Academic interest, work-life balance, future job market, compensation
It's the only thing I don't hate. Slightly less facetiously, I was very interested in the finer aspects of flaps, wound healing, function etc as it ties in to surgery and this fits in to plastics.
Diversity of practice environment combining medical management, surgery, and primary prevention
Subject matter interest, research background, lifestyle considerations
Work-life balance, enjoy subject matter, length of residency
Lifestyle, future job security, enjoy the marriage of psychology and medicine
I enjoy the topics and procedures
ability to use knowledge from preclinical years, personality fit, being able to oversee the process of evaluating, working up, and treating a patient
Resuscitation, procedures, pharm/phys, didn't like ED workflow
Interest in developmental disabilities, mentors in the field, fellow child neuro applicants
Personalities of colleagues; Interest in neuroMSK; lifestyle (regular hours, less call and weekends)

Personality of attendings within the field. Predominance of generally positive outcomes, patients motivated to get better. "Dynamic" surgically meaning the array of tech/tools/techniques is far more variable than other fields. Have had a personal athletic/fitness/injury background. My research mentor was just amazing as a human, served as great mascot of the field for me.

Clinical exposure opened my eyes to the reality of neurology day-to-day. i like the practitioners and people in neurology. It is an emerging and very exciting field right now. It has a lower barrier to entry and less competitiveness than some other specialties.

Knew I wanted to go into surgery, like the anatomy, like the types of procedures/working with hardware, good mix of healthy and sick patients.  There are a lot of subspecialty options and ways to tailor your future career to your ideal practice.
Diversity of patients, "second best" at every specialty, specialist in resuscitation
Have always been interested in neurology (came into medical school thinking neurology): I like the localization and precision that neurology allows
Enjoyed balance specialty offers of medicine, procedures, also pay, work/life balance, job market
Research opportunities, PSTP, Funding, and Procedures
Life style, intellectual interest, variety of practice, and unique opportunities to tailor career

Need for broad base of medical knowledge, ability to be front-lines to the community (and the opportunity to advocate for that community), great mix of medical and procedural practice, and really getting an undifferentiated patient
Patient population, residents at RBC, attendings at RBC
third year rotation sold me on it (diversity of practice, variety of potential career paths within specialty, advocacy opportunities, mix of surgery and medicine)
Learned more about it on 4th year rotations
Wanted to be able to do it all from critical care to primary care and see all ages.

Enjoyed the pathologies on my core rotation and on internal medicine, loved the team i worked with on the core and felt really supported/mentored. The other surgical subspecialty rotation i was very interested in was a disappointing rotation for me and my mentor in that field had been frustrating to work with
I enjoyed my rotation and I felt like this specialty fit well with my skill set and personality.

Surgeon personality, hate long rounding, love being in the OR, loved MSK week and ortho lectures, enjoyed my time when i tried shadowing, played sports in high school, have active lifestyle, like learning about MSK anatomy and pathology, its one of the only fields in medicine where you can fix something instead of managing conditions, want to help others be able to have a better lifestyle
Interested in conditions treated by neurosurgeons
Variety, spectrum of patient care (follow up in clinic, surgery, emergencies)
Liked patient population, mix of surgery and primary care, opportunities for advocacy
I want to subspecialize in either cardiology or pulm/crit
Enjoy anatomy and surgeries. Healthy patients and elective surgeries. Good salary. Good cultural fit.
Interest in content (pathology treated) and day to day schedule (active in OR); interest in subspecialty in future
I did research in the specialty prior to coming to medical school and the science really interests me and the clinical aspect is just as exciting

I liked the people that I met in the specialty during MSK week, found somewhat interesting research opportunities, and thought it woudl make for a stable career with ample opportunities to earn a high income.

column2: Did the order of your core clerkships have an impact on your choice of specialty?

column1: Q44 - Please briefly explain how the order of your core clerkships impacted your choice of specialty:
Please briefly explain how the order of your core clerkships impacted your choice of specialty:
Internal medicine coming after surgery cemented my desire to pursue it. I was also much more comfortable as it was towards the end of my third year.
Having my chosen specialty early in my third year allowed me to find mentors early and plan for my fourth year with enough time
Internal medicine was the first clerkship.
It was my last rotation so I knew by then that it was obviously better than anything that came before it.
I came to really love psychiatry and was very successful in my AI so had i seen it sooner i may have switched away from pathology
Was able to take an early elective in cardiac surgery since I completed my surgery core first
Had psychiatry near the end, best opportunity to compare with other specialties as they were all done
My chosen specialty was my last clerkship, and delayed my decision significantly (the rotation was also affected by covid).
Exposure to other specialties I hated
Almost hoped I would not like my last rotation (surgery) so that I would not have to make a difficult decision late in the process.
more excitement at the beginning, covid-19 shortened later rotations

I felt less likely to choose specialties related to my core rotations later in the year, because I had to schedule acting internships and electives for 4th year prior to completing many rotations and I did not know if I liked them or not
Having mine later allowed me to realize that I liked it more than everything I had done previously with no hesitation
having surgery early gave me flexibility
Could not do away rotations earlier.
might have considered psychiatry more strongly had it not been the last rotation

Yes I had ob gyn first and didn’t know I’d be interested. Whereas if I had ob gyn last after having to make a decision for aways I might have decided on general surgery as it was my 2nd favorite rotation

My experience on my core clerkship in my given specialty was relatively negative, partly because it was my first rotation and I was still unsure about what the role of a third year medical student was on the care team. Was not sure how much clinical initiative was appropriate!
I was not exposed to clinical practice in my chosen specialty until my last core clerkship.
I made sure to do neurology in the middle so I had IM before neuro
I didn't have IM first or last, it was squarely in the middle and I felt prepared and also able to tie my IM knowledge into future clerkships
I had desired specialty last, so I was very comfortable in a hospital setting and with basics of clinical care by the time I got to my specialty
Probably would have continued with EM or had to take a year off if my surgery rotation hadn’t been prior to December of my third year
I had time to explore other specialties and get used to inpatient care during 3rd year so I could compare my internal med rotation to those and not be worrying about learning the EMR for example
Waited too long in the year to do surgery clerkship and felt burnt out by the time I did Core 4 and didn't perform as well.
If I had had OBGYN earlier I may have chosen that. There seemed to be a pressure to choose come Jan Of third year and at that point I had only done surgery and Neuro
Made it more difficult to commit earlier to a surgical specialty since my core clerkship in surgery was later
Early exposure to surgery and medicine allowed me to choose between them.
Early enough to know what subspecialties I enjoyed. planning M4 for a competitive survival sub would be impossible with a late surgery rotation
Psychiatry was one of my last rotations, would have liked earlier to decide earlier

I had ob gym before pediatrics so I could directly compare the two specialities I was interested in. Additionally I had these two in Jan and feb so there was still some time to get AIs in both and plan my elective for the month of March accordingly. Had I had Ob gyn at the end I likely would not have been able to pursue that specialty since all AI spots filled quickly.
My surgery clerkship, which I was previously interested in, was in the middle, which helped me decide I did not want to pursue it. If I had surgery last I may have stuck with it
I completed surgery before IM, and then did an early AI in IM just after my IM clerkship, which showed me that I really enjoy IM even though I had started to consider surgery
my very last one was obgyn. think i would have considered it more strongly if i didn't literally have all my AIs, electives, letter writers, plans etc selected. that said I still would have done IM

I think you need a "not sure" option for this question. I think order of rotation will always impact specialty interest, but in ways that you can't plan for. Who knows what I'd be going into if, for example, I'd had an ortho rotation earlier in my M3 year and met a research mentor, or had a less miserable group of Ob/Gyn residents on that rotation. There's a lot of room for serendipity to occur in this process. And just as much room for the negative version of serendipity.
Seeing general surgery early enough helped me plan electives in surgical sub specialties to ensure gen surg was right for me

I had an early clerkship in neurology, which made me strongly consider going into neurology. But then I had my IM clerkship later in the year and then did my AIs in medicine and neurology later in the year to make my final decision
I had surgery at the end which made the decision a little more difficult.
I also enjoyed my psychiatry rotation, but this was my last rotation and occurred after I had already begun preparing to apply in OB/GYN
I did IM first and that shaped how I thought about patients
I would have been more willing to consider other surgical subspecialties had my general surgery clerkship not been last
confirmed that i liked the lifestyle
I felt pressured to decide on a chosen specialty prior to completing my Surgery/EM rotation in Spring of MS3 year. I would have liked to experience EM prior to making this decision.
having surgery first allowed me to see what the life of surgery was
I had an early rotation in my chosen specialty
Im not sure I would've done neurology if it was last, but I think that is because I would've had to scramble to find appropriate AIs, electives, etc. to satisfy residency applicaiton requirements.

I went into third year expecting to go into a different surgical specialty, ended up getting experience in different surgical fields, liked ortho more.  I had my surgery clerkship last and purposefully did a week of ortho during that clerkship in order to get more exposure to the field.  If I had surgery as my first clerkship before knowing I wanted to seek out that clinical exposure, I may not have had that experience that proved critical in my decision to pursue my chosen specialty.
Allowed me to explore broad options first before narrowing down my choices
I did emergency medicine last and didnt like anything before

I thought I wanted to do ENT and if that had been my first rotation I probably would have liked the rotation way more (I was annoyed partially by the lack of autonomy). Also the longitudinal track allowed me to get exposure to everything else before surgery, so I felt confident ruling everything else out without the disadvantage of having it in spring.
Had surgery first - confirmed interest in surgery. Did not consider medical specialties as much
Having opportunity to do electives early on and doing surgery early.
I believe if I had done surgery before medicine I might have decided to go into a surgical specialty
Late exposure to IM in third year
I did IM early and gave me more time to think
